         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
               <lb n="2"/>
               <expan><abbr>Fil</abbr><ex>io</ex></expan>
               <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Victor">Victori</name>
               </persName>.
               <lb n="3"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Attia">Attia</name>
               </persName> ITCINIA CO
               <lb break="no" n="4"/>IUEL bene merenti
               <lb n="5"/>et <expan><abbr>fil</abbr><ex>ii</ex></expan> fecerunt.
            </ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine Spirits. To (her?) son Victor. Attia ITCINIACOIUEL and (her)
               sons made this for (him), well-deserving.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription appears to be a modern forgery based on CIL 6.28921. Note the
               letters running together without distinction between individual words in line 2, the
               upper case “U” in “fecerunt” in line 5, and the perfectly rounded interpuncts between
               words in line 2, before “bene merenti” in line 4, and after “et” in line 5. (Peter
               Lech) Note also the fixed-width font. Since CIL 6.28921 is from Rome, this
               inscription was probably also manufactured there.</p>
         </div>
